text: I think to your point, when most people think about when they think of option strategies, they think of call overwriting, for example, or cash secured put selling, or certain types of hedging activity, you know, things that typically would have significant directional market exposure to them. So you think of, you know, call overwriting or put writing, for example, both of those are long equity market exposures. And on a, you know, day to day or month to month basis, really, the equity market exposure is going to be the biggest risk factor. And then there will be other risk factors, you know, second and third order beneath those, but really market exposure is the biggest driver. I would contrast that with volatility strategies, broadly defined and broadly speaking, which really try to isolate features of the distribution of returns, but not really the direction of returns. So for example, instead of having views on whether the S&P is going to be a good thing or not, if the S&P will go up or down, volatility investors might think about things like, how volatile is the S&P 500 likely to be over the next month, compared to the Russell 2000, for example, or maybe, you know, if the equity market goes down 2% tomorrow, where's the VIX going to be? And constructing, you know, bets and views on aspects of the probability distribution of returns and cross sectionally within the universe or within the same market. So I think that's really the key distinction, sort of, is the first order exposure to the underlying market direction, or the other features of the probability distribution.
